 meta-package (v3.x) which includes the test framework, adapter, and test SDK\n4. **Update Test SDK**: The `MSTest` v3 meta-package includes `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk`, so we can remove the separate reference\n\nWait, I need to verify the framework requirements for MSTest v3 — it might actually support .NET Framework 4.6.2 or require .NET 6+.\n\nSo the migration path is clearer now: I'm removing the old assembly reference and replacing it with the unified `MSTest` NuGet package (v3.x), which bundles the test framework, adapter, and SDK together. The namespace remains `Microsoft.VisualStudio.TestTools.UnitTesting`, and this single package reference handles everything the old separate references did. I should also check what target frameworks MSTest v3 actually supports. .NET Framework 4.6.2+, so net462 should still work. But the user might want to upgrade to a modern TFM. I'll suggest the minimal changes needed and mention the TFM upgrade as optional.\n\nActually, looking more carefully: MSTest v3 (3.0+) does support net462. The `MSTest` SDK-style package works with it.\n\nThe changes needed:\n1. Remove `<Reference Include=\"Microsoft.VisualStudio.QualityTools.UnitTestFramework\" />`\n2. Replace `<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk\" Version=\"17.5.0\" />` with `<PackageReference Include=\"MSTest\" Version=\"3.8.2\" />` (or latest v3)\n3. The C# code doesn't need changes - the namespace and attributes are the same\n\nFor the package structure, the unified `MSTest` package is the recommended v3 approach rather than managing the individual components separately. I could also use the `<Project Sdk=\"MSTest\">` approach, which is the most modern way and automatically handles all the dependencies. Since MSTest v3 introduced this SDK pattern, I'll go with that as the cleanest upgrade path—it sets sensible defaults for test projects and eliminates manual configuration.\n\nLet me implement this with the SDK approach and provide clear guidance on what changed and